claim: The study shows that women's participation in the labour market has had opposite effects in Italy and Hungary: in Italy, women's employment is negatively associated with first motherhood (e.g. Santarelli 2011; Vignoli et al. 2012) whereas in Hungary childbearing propensity is higher among the employed women (Spe´der and Kamara`s 2008).

claim: The study shows that in Italy, the increase in female labour market participation was found to be associated with a small but significant increase in the conditional probability of having a first child, whereas in Hungary it was not significant.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents the results of the authors' analysis on the relationship between female labour market participation and fertility in Italy and Hungary.
title: The Effect Of Women'S Participation In The Labour Market On The Postponement Of First Childbirth: A Comparison Of Italy And Hungary

claim: The study shows that unemployment also appears to be linked to fertility postponement. As was mentioned above, the literature has posited that during periods of economic uncertainty and rising unemployment, individuals postpone both marriage and motherhood. The effect of regional unemployment trends on fertility in Italy confirmed these studies: the increase in the female unemployment rate led to a postponement in women making long-term, binding commitments.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents the results of the authors' analysis on the relationship between unemployment and fertility postponement in Italy.
title: The Effect Of Women'S Participation In The Labour Market On The Postponement Of First Childbirth: A Comparison Of Italy And Hungary

claim: The study shows that in Hungary, women encountered difficulties in entering the labour market after the dissolution of the socialist state.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents the results of the authors' analysis on the impact of political and economic changes on women's labour market participation in Hungary.
title: The Effect Of Women'S Participation In The Labour Market On The Postponement Of First Childbirth: A Comparison Of Italy And Hungary

claim: The study shows that in both Italy and Hungary, women adjust their aspirations on the basis of their education, their age, and their position in the labour market, including in the regional labour market.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents the results of the authors' analysis on the relationship between individual characteristics, labour market participation, and fertility postponement in Italy and Hungary.
title: The Effect Of Women'S Participation In The Labour Market On The Postponement Of First Childbirth: A Comparison Of Italy And Hungary

claim: The study shows that in Hungary, the increase in female educational levels (the increase of the percentage of women with tertiary education and a corresponding decrease in the percentage with secondary education only), combined with the protracted duration of university studies, contributes to a postponement of the entire transition to adulthood, and also of motherhood.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents the results of the authors' analysis on the relationship between educational levels and fertility postponement in Hungary.
title: The Effect Of Women'S Participation In The Labour Market On The Postponement Of First Childbirth: A Comparison Of Italy And Hungary

claim: The study shows that in Italy, the trend towards postponement appears to have started in the northern region, spread rapidly to the centre, and then spread to the south of the country a generation later.

claim: Couples' intentions are associated with child well-being through mothers' depressive symptoms, mother involvement, and the co-parental relationship dynamic.
explanation: Both parents intending the birth (rather than neither parent) has positive indirect effects on child well-being by increasing mother involvement, reducing mothers' depressive symptoms, and fostering a positive coparental relationship dynamic. I did not find support for hypotheses that only a father's intending the birth buffered the negative effects of a mother not intending the birth - which was a key finding from some of the recent work focusing on couples' intentions and maternal and child health during pregnancy (see Hohmann-Marriott, 2009; Martin et al., 2007). Rather, this suggests when examining parental involvement after the birth and child well-being at later ages, a mother's intending the birth can buffer the negative effects of a father not intending the birth.

claim: The authors find that around 20% of the group who were childless at age 30 said they do not intend to have a child, while around 20% said they are unsure.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating the prevalence of uncertainty about fertility intentions among the sample.
title: Chapter 3 Childlessness In The Uk

claim: The authors find that around 30% of those who were childless at age 30 and who said they intend to have a child remained childless at age 42.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating the underachievement of fertility intentions among the sample.
title: Chapter 3 Childlessness In The Uk

claim: The authors find that around one-third of childless respondents said they had not wanted children, and two in ten said they had never met the right person.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating the most common reasons given by childless respondents for not having had children.
title: Chapter 3 Childlessness In The Uk

claim: Son preference is associated with an increase in girls' relative burden of housework.
explanation: The study finds that when there is a preference for sons, the gap in the time spent on housework for a girl over a boy increases by 2.27 hours (linear model, the original specification for son preference), 0.74 hours (linear model, dummy variable specification for son preference), 0.46 hours (two-part model), or grows by 11.6% (negative binomial regression, dummy variable specification for son preference).
title: Acknowledgements

claim: A mismatch between desired and actual living arrangements brings about psychological discomforts to older parents.
explanation: The study finds that experiencing a discrepancy in living arrangements is associated with an 11% (= exp(0.105)) increase in negative affect for independent living parents, and a 14% (=exp (0.064+0.062)) increase in negative affect for parents coresiding with a married child.
title: Acknowledgements

claim: 'During the most acute phase of the pandemic, in spring 2020, governments around the world placed limits on mobility, recommending that people stay at home for their own safety and that of others.'
explanation: The authors state that during the COVID-19 pandemic, governments worldwide implemented lockdown measures limiting mobility.
title: Stuck Under The Rainbow? Gay Parents' Experiences With Transnational Surrogacy And Family

claim: 'These transnational practices of becoming parents have important emotional, ethical, physical, psychological, and economic implications.'
explanation: The authors claim that transnational surrogacy practices have significant emotional, ethical, physical, psychological, and economic consequences.
title: Stuck Under The Rainbow? Gay Parents' Experiences With Transnational Surrogacy And Family

claim: 'In Italy, the media have given little visibility to this situation. And at least during the first phase of the virus, also international media coverage on how transnational surrogacy practices were affected by the pandemic lacked the voices and viewpoints of commissioning parents blocked by the lockdown.'
explanation: The authors claim that Italian and international media have given little attention to the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic on transnational surrogacy, particularly from the perspective of commissioning parents affected by lockdown.
title: Stuck Under The Rainbow? Gay Parents' Experiences With Transnational Surrogacy And Family

claim: The analysis confirms that female education is the dominant socioeconomic driver of fertility transitions in the developing world.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating the importance of female education in driving fertility transitions.
title: Table Of Contents

claim: The long-standing decline in the propensity to bear a third child, which was the driving force of the fertility decline until the mid-1980s, has probably ended.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis of period parity progression rates in Austria.
title: Table Of Contents

claim: The increase in age at first birth can be observed in all education groups and is not only the result of staying in the education system for a longer time (Städtner and Spielauer 2002).
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis of the relationship between age at first birth and education groups.
title: Table Of Contents

claim: The ongoing fertility postponement has negatively affected the overall first birth progression rates, for which Figure 8 shows both the unadjusted version (based on age-specific first birth probabilities) and the adjusted version. explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis of period parity progression rates and their relationship with tempo effects.

claim: The lack of data on fertility by birth order for the period prior to 1984 limits our analysis of parity-specific trends to the past two decades, which were characterized by relatively stable fertility rates.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a limitation in the author's study based on the availability of data.

claim: The focus of our article is Hungary, where the very low fertility rate—which has been below 1.5 births per woman since the mid-1990s—projects a demographically unsustainable population.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating the low fertility rate and its implications for Hungary's population.
title: Who Remains Childless? Unrealised Fertility Plans In Hungary*

claim: Our article is structured as follows. The background section provides an overview of the main childlessness-related demographic trends in Europe, including the post-socialist countries and Hungary.
explanation: This claim is not a new original finding but rather a statement about the structure of the paper.
title: Who Remains Childless? Unrealised Fertility Plans In Hungary*

claim: Present-day aging Europe, characterised not only by a decline in the proportion of young people, but also by low fertility, postponed childbearing, and an increase in childlessness among younger generations, can be divided into three demographically distinct areas.
explanation: This claim is not a new original finding but rather a statement about the current state of Europe's demographic trends.
title: Who Remains Childless? Unrealised Fertility Plans In Hungary*

claim: Regarding becoming a parent, a higher level of education is less of a negatively determining factor for men than it is for women—although men with higher qualifications can also delay becoming parents if they start their careers in the labour market later, but in their case there is no strict biologically determined age limit to becoming a parent.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on previous research and the author's analysis, indicating differences between men and women regarding education and parenthood.
title: Who Remains Childless? Unrealised Fertility Plans In Hungary*

claim: In the present study, especially when we examine the life events (or nonevents) of respondents in the fi rst three waves of the Hungarian Generations and Gender Survey (GGS), we attempt to combine the explanatory forces of the life course framework with the earlier mentioned postponement transition, second demographic transition as well as the constrained capabilities approaches.
explanation: This claim is not a new original finding but rather a statement about the methodology used in the study.
title: Who Remains Childless? Unrealised Fertility Plans In Hungary*

claim: Our empirical analysis based on Kaplan-Meier survival estimates also shed light on the upper age limits of childbearing in our 2001 sample (see Diagrams I and II in the Appendix).
explanation: This claim is not a new original finding but rather a statement about the methods used in the study.
title: Who Remains Childless? Unrealised Fertility Plans In Hungary*

claim: The relationship between labour income and first birth depends on the age of the woman.
explanation: The authors find that higher gross weekly incomes are associated with a higher risk of first birth from around the age of 30. Prior to the age of 30, medium level incomes are associated with a higher risk.
title: The Influence Of Income And Work Hours On First Birth For Australian Women

claim: Part-time employment may facilitate childbearing.
explanation: The authors find that working part-time, around 3 days per week, increases the risk of first birth relative to working shorter part-time hours or full-time or longer.
title: The Influence Of Income And Work Hours On First Birth For Australian Women

claim: The inclusion of working time in measures of income may affect the results of statistical analyses.
explanation: The authors suggest that examining only a main (age-independent) effect of gross weekly wages may mask some differences in first family formation when considered in isolation.
title: The Influence Of Income And Work Hours On First Birth For Australian Women

claim: The analysis confirms that female education is the dominant socioeconomic driver of fertility transitions in the developing world.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating the importance of female education in driving fertility transitions.
title: Childlessness In Twentieth-Century Spain: A Cohort Analysis For Women Born 1920–1969

claim: The reproductive behaviour of Spanish women followed a similar pattern of change during the same period as American women.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it compares and contrasts the reproductive behaviour of Spanish and American women, based on the author's analysis.
title: Childlessness In Twentieth-Century Spain: A Cohort Analysis For Women Born 1920–1969

claim: The relationship between marriage, education and childlessness among cohorts born in the twentieth century appeared to change in a very profound way, relatively independent of the compositional transformation of American society.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating a shift in the relationship between marriage, education and childlessness among cohorts born in the twentieth century.
title: Childlessness In Twentieth-Century Spain: A Cohort Analysis For Women Born 1920–1969

claim: The goal of this paper is to focus on Spanish women born between 1920 and 1969 so as to analyse the factors that enable us to understand these long-term trends in childlessness.
explanation: This claim states the purpose of the study, which is an original contribution as it focuses on a specific population and time period.
title: Childlessness In Twentieth-Century Spain: A Cohort Analysis For Women Born 1920–1969

claim: The possibility of opposing effects on trends in childlessness coming from composition and rates has already been carefully observed in the USA (Hayford 2013) and cannot be discarded in Spain.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it refers to a previous study that found opposing effects on trends in childlessness, suggesting that similar dynamics may exist in Spain.
title: Childlessness In Twentieth-Century Spain: A Cohort Analysis For Women Born 1920–1969

claim: The authors aim to build on the findings of relevant literature in order to track the evolution in childlessness over much of the twentieth century in Spain, explaining the main changes that have taken place and testing the extent to which the changing links between education, marriage and childlessness among more recent cohorts identified directly in the USA and indirectly in other European countries can be also found in Spain.
explanation: This claim states the aim of the study, which is an original contribution as it builds on previous literature and aims to test its findings in a new context.
title: Childlessness In Twentieth-Century Spain: A Cohort Analysis For Women Born 1920–1969

claim: The data for these analyses come from the Intergenerational Panel Study of Mothers and Children, an 18-year panel study started from a systematic probability sample of children born in the Detroit metropolitan area (Wayne, Oakland, and Macomb Counties).
explanation: The authors explicitly state that this is the source of their data.
title: The Influence Of Early Life Course Religious Exposure On Young Adults' Dispositions Toward Childbearing

claim: In 1980, a full 87 percent of the families were still involved in the study (Axinn and Thornton 1996).
explanation: The authors cite a source to support their claim that a large proportion of the respondents remained in the study.
title: The Influence Of Early Life Course Religious Exposure On Young Adults' Dispositions Toward Childbearing

claim: Although research provides reason to distinguish among religions in their effects on childbearing disposition, it is clear that all Judeo-Christian religions encourage childbearing to some extent.
explanation: The authors make a claim based on previous literature about the role of religion in encouraging childbearing.
title: The Influence Of Early Life Course Religious Exposure On Young Adults' Dispositions Toward Childbearing

claim: Exposure may have a cumulative effect, and may be comprised of the theological perspective connected to parental religious affiliation, experiences emanating from parental religious participation, personal levels of participation in religious services and activities, and the personal importance of religion in day-to-day life.
explanation: The authors present a claim about the various ways exposure to religion may influence childbearing dispositions.
title: The Influence Of Early Life Course Religious Exposure On Young Adults' Dispositions Toward Childbearing

claim: These children will more often have strategies for adulthood that include having children (and more of them) than those with religiously uninvolved parents.
explanation: The authors make a claim about the impact of religious exposure on childbearing strategies.
title: The Influence Of Early Life Course Religious Exposure On Young Adults' Dispositions Toward Childbearing

claim: Religious organizations often encourage reproduction in indirect ways as well. Many churches elevate the value of families by sponsoring family retreats, classes on parenthood, and family counseling.
explanation: The authors claim that religious organizations promote reproduction through various means.
title: The Influence Of Early Life Course Religious Exposure On Young Adults' Dispositions Toward Childbearing

claim: Religious participation also leads to social interaction with others who value parenthood, producing an effect of social closure that may reinforce pro-natalist values.
explanation: The authors claim that religious participation can lead to increased social interaction with pro-natalist individuals.
title: The Influence Of Early Life Course Religious Exposure On Young Adults' Dispositions Toward Childbearing

explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating the importance of female education in driving fertility transitions.
title: Why Childless Men And Women Give Up On Having Children

claim: The study investigates the reasons why childless men and women who originally were considering having children gave up on having them during their life course.
explanation: This claim is an original research question presented by the authors.
title: Why Childless Men And Women Give Up On Having Children

claim: The results of our multinomial logistic regression models show that different mechanisms explain why childless men and women give up on having children.
explanation: This claim is a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating the originality of their findings.
title: Why Childless Men And Women Give Up On Having Children

claim: Respondents with a partner who highly valued living in a partnership were more likely to have given up on having children.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating the importance of partnership in the decision to give up on having children.
title: Why Childless Men And Women Give Up On Having Children

claim: Giving up on having children was less likely if respondents anticipated positive consequences of parenthood and more likely if they anticipated negative consequences.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating the importance of perceived benefits and costs in the decision to give up on having children.
title: Why Childless Men And Women Give Up On Having Children

claim: Women were more likely to have given up on having children than men.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating gender differences in the decision to give up on having children.
title: Why Childless Men And Women Give Up On Having Children

claim: Respondents who were employed were less likely to have given up on having children.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating the importance of employment in the decision to give up on having children.
title: Why Childless Men And Women Give Up On Having Children

claim: Respondents with high emotional autonomy were more likely to be found in the 'permanently considering having children' group and the 'permanently not considering having children' group.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating the importance of personality traits in the decision to have or not have children.
title: Why Childless Men And Women Give Up On Having Children

claim: Respondents who reported that their parents wanted them to have children were more likely to belong to the 'permanently considering having children' group.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating the influence of parental expectations on the decision to have children.
title: Why Childless Men And Women Give Up On Having Children

claim: The demographic challenge Europe is facing due to long-term low fertility, accompanied by pronounced economic uncertainty, indicates the need for adequate policy response based on a thorough understanding of the economic uncertainty– fertility decisions–public policy nexus.
explanation: The authors state that there is a need for policy responses based on an understanding of the relationship between economic uncertainty and fertility decisions.
title: Economic Uncertainty And First-Birth Intentions In Europe

claim: Societal economic uncertainty is negatively associated with short-term parenthood intentions, especially for men.
explanation: The authors find a negative association between societal economic uncertainty and short-term parenthood intentions, specifically for men.
title: Economic Uncertainty And First-Birth Intentions In Europe

claim: Regarding subjective economic security, men's labour market position matters irrespectively of the institutional context, but women's labour market position matters at younger ages only and in particular welfare regimes (the Postsocialist and Familialistic regimes).
explanation: The authors find that men's labour market position is important for subjective economic security regardless of the institutional context, while women's labour market position matters at younger ages and in specific welfare regimes.
title: Economic Uncertainty And First-Birth Intentions In Europe

claim: Perceived income security is less important at higher ages for either gender and for women below age 30, especially in the aftermath of the crisis.
explanation: The authors find that perceived income security becomes less important at higher ages for both genders, and for women below age 30, particularly in the aftermath of the crisis.
title: Economic Uncertainty And First-Birth Intentions In Europe

claim: Men in their early thirties show the lowest fatherhood intentions in a constrained situation.
explanation: The authors find that men in their early thirties have the lowest intentions to become fathers in a constrained economic situation.
title: Economic Uncertainty And First-Birth Intentions In Europe

claim: For young employed women, a secure position is a precondition for first birth, but motherhood appears as attractive alternative to unemployment above age 30, except for Postsocialist and Universal clusters.
explanation: The authors find that for young employed women, a secure position is necessary for first birth, but motherhood becomes an attractive alternative to unemployment for women above age 30, with the exception of the Postsocialist and Universal clusters.
title: Economic Uncertainty And First-Birth Intentions In Europe

claim: The analysis confirms that the Coale-McNeil marriage model can replicate first birth distributions and has demonstrated its usefulness in their analysis.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating the importance of the Coale-McNeil marriage model in studying age at first birth.
title: What Are The Determinants Of **Delayed** Childbearing And Permanent Childlessness In The United **States?**

claim: The extended version of the Coale-McNeil model proposed by Trussell and Bloom can account for covariate effects on the parameters of age at first birth.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating the usefulness of the extended Coale-McNeil model in studying the determinants of age at first birth.
title: What Are The Determinants Of **Delayed** Childbearing And Permanent Childlessness In The United **States?**

claim: The results suggest that delayed childbearing and increasing childlessness are phenomena primarily associated with recent cohorts.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating a changing pattern of fertility behavior in recent cohorts.
title: What Are The Determinants Of **Delayed** Childbearing And Permanent Childlessness In The United **States?**

claim: The results provide strong evidence that education is positively associated with delayed childbearing and increasing childlessness.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating the importance of education in delaying childbearing and increasing childlessness.
title: What Are The Determinants Of **Delayed** Childbearing And Permanent Childlessness In The United **States?**

claim: The results suggest that being Catholic has an insignificant effect on age at first birth.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating no significant effect of being Catholic on age at first birth.
title: What Are The Determinants Of **Delayed** Childbearing And Permanent Childlessness In The United **States?**

claim: The results provide strong evidence that race has an insignificant effect on childlessness.

title: Fertility In Advanced Societies: A Review Of Research La Fe´Condite´ Dans Les Socie´Te´S Avance´Es: Un Examen Des Recherches

claim: The study demonstrates that welfare regimes, such as Nordic socio-democratic countries or market provision (Anglo-Saxon liberal market regimes), enable higher fertility.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating the impact of welfare regimes on fertility.
title: Fertility In Advanced Societies: A Review Of Research La Fe´Condite´ Dans Les Socie´Te´S Avance´Es: Un Examen Des Recherches

claim: The study shows that ideational changes, such as the rejection of institutional control and accentuation of individual autonomy, are driving forces of new family arrangements and behaviors.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating the impact of ideational changes on family arrangements and behaviors.
title: Fertility In Advanced Societies: A Review Of Research La Fe´Condite´ Dans Les Socie´Te´S Avance´Es: Un Examen Des Recherches

claim: The study demonstrates that the spread of modern contraception has radically changed the nature of the fertility decision-making and contributed to the reduction in the number of children and the postponement of childbearing.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating the impact of contraception on fertility.
title: Fertility In Advanced Societies: A Review Of Research La Fe´Condite´ Dans Les Socie´Te´S Avance´Es: Un Examen Des Recherches

claim: 'The accuracy of research on infertility hinges critically on the way infertility is conceptualized and measured.'
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating the importance of considering how infertility is conceptualized and measured in research.
title: Reimagining Infertility: A Critical Examination Of Fertility Norms, Geopolitics And Survey Bias

claim: 'Invisibilization, by definition an exclusionary process, is problematic within a broader global development agenda.'
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents the authors' argument that invisibilization is problematic in the context of global development.
title: Reimagining Infertility: A Critical Examination Of Fertility Norms, Geopolitics And Survey Bias

claim: 'The infertility of some groups has been rendered invisible by their exclusion from common tracking methods.'
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating that certain groups have been excluded from common infertility tracking methods.
title: Reimagining Infertility: A Critical Examination Of Fertility Norms, Geopolitics And Survey Bias

claim: 'The reproductive imaginary'—prevailing social beliefs about who can and should reproduce—shape the design and conclusions of infertility research.'
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating that the reproductive imaginary influences the design and conclusions of infertility research.
title: Reimagining Infertility: A Critical Examination Of Fertility Norms, Geopolitics And Survey Bias

claim: 'The limits of our reproductive imaginaries also bias how we generate infertility estimates.'
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating that the limits of our reproductive imaginaries influence how infertility estimates are generated.
title: Reimagining Infertility: A Critical Examination Of Fertility Norms, Geopolitics And Survey Bias

claim: The study investigates how childbearing motives shape fertility desires and intentions of childless individuals, who have reached the age when the final decision for or against reproduction has to be taken.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's research, indicating that childbearing motives influence fertility decisions in childless individuals.
title: From Motives Through Desires To Intentions: Investigating The Reproductive Choices Of Childless Men And Women In Poland

claim: The study aims to verify whether in the specific sample of Polish, childless individuals, positive and negative childbearing motives (PCM and NCM) are related to childbearing desires and intentions, as postulated in Miller's theoretical model (Miller, 1994).
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a research question based on the author's use of Miller's theoretical model, indicating that the authors aim to test the relationship between childbearing motives and desires/intentions in their study.
title: From Motives Through Desires To Intentions: Investigating The Reproductive Choices Of Childless Men And Women In Poland

claim: The results confirm that for childless individuals, in the analysed specific age range, childbearing desires are good predictors of reproductive intentions.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's research, indicating that childbearing desires can predict reproductive intentions in childless individuals.
title: From Motives Through Desires To Intentions: Investigating The Reproductive Choices Of Childless Men And Women In Poland

claim: The study provides support for the theoretical framework of Warren Miller, documenting its applicability in the new research context: in the new cultural setting and in a specific subpopulation.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's research, indicating that Miller's theoretical framework has been successfully applied to a new cultural setting and subpopulation.
title: From Motives Through Desires To Intentions: Investigating The Reproductive Choices Of Childless Men And Women In Poland

claim: Unemployment leads to earlier entries into parenthood for both men and women.
explanation: The authors find that unemployment has a positive relationship with transition into parenthood for both men and women.
title: Unemployment And The Timing Of Parenthood: Implications Of Partnership Status And Partner'S Employment

claim: The impact of unemployment on the timing of parenthood differs according to the relationship status in which it is experienced.
explanation: The authors argue that the effect of unemployment on fertility decisions varies depending on the partnership status during which it takes place.
title: Unemployment And The Timing Of Parenthood: Implications Of Partnership Status And Partner'S Employment

claim: Among married individuals, the timing of parenthood is determined largely by the labour market status of the female partner.
explanation: The authors find that among married couples, male unemployment has a negative effect on the probability of having a first child, whereas female unemployment has a positive effect.
title: Unemployment And The Timing Of Parenthood: Implications Of Partnership Status And Partner'S Employment

claim: Cohabiting couples' fertility behaviour is markedly different from that of married couples.
explanation: The authors find that for cohabiting couples, both male and female unemployment are associated with earlier entry into parenthood.
title: Unemployment And The Timing Of Parenthood: Implications Of Partnership Status And Partner'S Employment

claim: The analysis confirms that the introduction of statutory maternity leave (in other words, the right of reinstatement into the previous job) in 1976 caused a postponement of first births.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating that the introduction of statutory maternity leave had an impact on first birth timing.
title: Eligibility For Maternity Leave And First Birth Timing In Great Britain

claim: The study finds that women who were eligible for maternity leave and pay had higher rates of transition to first birth than those who were not.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating that eligibility for maternity leave and pay may have influenced decisions about when to have a first child.
title: Eligibility For Maternity Leave And First Birth Timing In Great Britain

claim: The study suggests that women planning to return to employment may have felt that it was beneficial to become established in their careers before deciding to have a first child, even independent of maternity leave.
explanation: This claim is an original interpretation based on the author's findings, suggesting that women's growing attachment to the labor market may have influenced fertility timing.
title: Eligibility For Maternity Leave And First Birth Timing In Great Britain

claim: The generosity of earner–carer support has a consistently positive association with fertility intentions at both parities for women.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating the importance of earner–carer support in influencing fertility intentions.
title: Family Policy And Fertility Intentions In 21 European Countries

claim: The generosity of traditional family support may be differentially related to parity-specific fertility intentions; this type of family support has a positive association with childless men's and women's intentions to have a first child in the next 3 years, whereas it loses its association (and turns negative) with both men's and women's intentions to have a second child in the next 3 years.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating the different impact of traditional family support on fertility intentions at various stages of family formation.
title: Family Policy And Fertility Intentions In 21 European Countries

claim: Family policy associations may vary with the educational level of the respondent, labor force status, and age of the youngest child.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating that family policy associations can differ depending on individual characteristics.
title: Family Policy And Fertility Intentions In 21 European Countries

claim: In women aged 15 - 49 years, we conducted a study to estimate population-based incident rates of clinically recorded fertility problems.
explanation: The authors explicitly state that they conducted a study to estimate population-based incident rates of clinically recorded fertility problems in women aged 15 - 49 years.

claim: We found the highest rates of clinically recorded fertility problems, approximately 1% of women per annum in women age 30–34 years.
explanation: The authors present a finding based on their analysis that shows the highest rates of clinically recorded fertility problems are approximately 1% of women per annum in women aged 30 – 34 years.

claim: We found little variation in rates by geographic area and importantly no variation by socioeconomic status in the overall rate that included women of all ages.
explanation: The authors present a finding based on their analysis that shows little variation in rates by geographic area and no variation by socioeconomic status in the overall rate that includes women of all ages.

claim: Recording of fertility problems, however, is closely related to socioeconomic patterns of women's age at first conception, indicating that many couples have pre-existing rather than specifically age-related infertility.
explanation: The authors present a conclusion based on their analysis that suggests recording of fertility problems is closely related to socioeconomic patterns of women's age at first conception, implying that many couples have pre-existing rather than specifically age-related infertility.

claim: Our data demonstrate that age-specific estimates in older more affluent women may be exaggerated by delaying conception.
explanation: The authors present a conclusion based on their analysis that demonstrates age-specific estimates in older, more affluent women may be exaggerated by delaying conception.

claim: Our rates also show some increase in fertility problems after the introduction of the national fertility treatment guidelines (National Collaborating Centre for Women's and Children's Health, 2004), which may reflect increased awareness and availability of fertility services.
explanation: The authors present a conclusion based on their analysis that suggests there is an increase in fertility problems after the introduction of national fertility treatment guidelines, potentially due to increased awareness and availability of fertility services.

claim: The aim of this study is to investigate whether the coupling of two low-educated partners may be associated with distinct patterns of childbearing behaviour in a wide array of European nations.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents the research question and objective of the study.
title: Comparative Population Studies Vol. 46 (2021): 533-554 (Date Of Release: 13.12.2021) Educational Pairings And Fertility Across Europe: How Do The Low-Educated Fare?

claim: Using data from the EU-SILC panel study (European Union Statistics on Income and Living Condition) from 22 European countries and discrete time event history models, we examine whether those couples with the lowest joint educational resources display differences in second and third (or higher) order birth transition rates compared with couples in which one of the two or both partners have achieved medium- or high (henceforth 'higher') educational attainment.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents the research methodology and analysis approach of the study.
title: Comparative Population Studies Vol. 46 (2021): 533-554 (Date Of Release: 13.12.2021) Educational Pairings And Fertility Across Europe: How Do The Low-Educated Fare?

claim: The new home economics approach, which originates from Becker's work in the early 1980s, suggested that partner role specialisation in labour market versus domestic work is the most effi cient system of family organisation.
explanation: This claim is a restatement of previous literature, but it is included here because it provides context and background for the hypotheses being tested in this study.
title: Comparative Population Studies Vol. 46 (2021): 533-554 (Date Of Release: 13.12.2021) Educational Pairings And Fertility Across Europe: How Do The Low-Educated Fare?

claim: Resource pooling theory predicts higher birth rates among couples with higher levels of pooled socioeconomic resources.
explanation: This claim is a restatement of previous literature, but it is included here because it provides context and background for the hypotheses being tested in this study.
title: Comparative Population Studies Vol. 46 (2021): 533-554 (Date Of Release: 13.12.2021) Educational Pairings And Fertility Across Europe: How Do The Low-Educated Fare?

claim: The relationship between educational pairings and progression to second and third births may be moderated by the social context of a given country.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a hypothesis about how the relationship between educational pairings and childbearing behaviour might vary across different countries.
title: Comparative Population Studies Vol. 46 (2021): 533-554 (Date Of Release: 13.12.2021) Educational Pairings And Fertility Across Europe: How Do The Low-Educated Fare?

claim: Couples with two low-educated partners can be expected to display the lowest birth transition rates to second and third births, because they have the fewest resources at their disposal.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a hypothesis about how the educational pairings of couples might affect their childbearing behaviour.
title: Comparative Population Studies Vol. 46 (2021): 533-554 (Date Of Release: 13.12.2021) Educational Pairings And Fertility Across Europe: How Do The Low-Educated Fare?

claim: High opportunity costs for women's care-related employment breaks could translate into lowest second and third birth rates for hypogamous couples, with a low-educated man and secondary- or tertiary-educated woman.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a hypothesis about how the educational pairings of couples might affect their childbearing behaviour.
title: Comparative Population Studies Vol. 46 (2021): 533-554 (Date Of Release: 13.12.2021) Educational Pairings And Fertility Across Europe: How Do The Low-Educated Fare?

claim: Assuming an equal distribution of fertility desires across educational pairings, hypogamous couples with a higher-educated woman and a low-educated man may display the highest transition rates to second or third births, in the case that she can use her potentially stronger economic standing to negotiate for more support with childrearing with him.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a hypothesis about how the educational pairings of couples might affect their childbearing behaviour.
title: Comparative Population Studies Vol. 46 (2021): 533-554 (Date Of Release: 13.12.2021) Educational Pairings And Fertility Across Europe: How Do The Low-Educated Fare?

claim: The partners' educational pairings may be less relevant for couples' second or third birth progressions among lower-educated couples.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a hypothesis about how the educational pairings of couples might affect their childbearing behaviour.
title: Comparative Population Studies Vol. 46 (2021): 533-554 (Date Of Release: 13.12.2021) Educational Pairings And Fertility Across Europe: How Do The Low-Educated Fare?

claim: The relationship between educational pairings and fertility may be moderated by the social context of a given country.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a hypothesis about how the relationship between educational pairings and childbearing behaviour might vary across different countries.
title: Comparative Population Studies Vol. 46 (2021): 533-554 (Date Of Release: 13.12.2021) Educational Pairings And Fertility Across Europe: How Do The Low-Educated Fare?

claim: 'The majority of couples want no more children (71% of wives, 68% of husbands).'
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the survey results, indicating that most couples in Japan do not want more children.

claim: 'Three children is the ideal number, according to 46% of wives; 41% believe that two is ideal.'
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the survey results, indicating that the majority of wives in Japan prefer three or two children as their ideal family size.

claim: 'Seventy-five percent of wives and 66% of husbands say they are very concerned or a little concerned about the recent fertility decline in their country.'
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the survey results, indicating that a majority of both wives and husbands in Japan are concerned about the declining fertility rate.

claim: 'The proportion of respondents who approve of government intervention to raise fertility levels has doubled since the last survey, to about 35% among both wives and husbands.'
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the survey results, indicating that there has been an increase in approval for government intervention to address declining fertility rates.

claim: 'Twenty-three percent of wives say this effort [to license a lowdose pill] is
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the survey results, indicating that a significant proportion of wives in Japan have opinions about the government's efforts to license a low-dose pill.

claim: 'Fiftythree percent of women with chlamydia also had anaerobic vaginosis, compared with 26% of those without chlamydia.'
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the study results, indicating a higher prevalence of anaerobic vaginosis in women with chlamydia.

claim: 'Ultimately, PID was diagnosed in 19 (63%) of the 30 women with chlamydia whom researchers were able to follow up.'
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the study results, indicating that a majority of women with chlamydia were diagnosed with pelvic inflammatory disease.

claim: This work makes two contributions to existing studies. First, it aims to explain childlessness by focusing on behavioural pathways leading to childlessness rather than considering contemporary correlates of childlessness or preferences for a childless lifestyle.
explanation: The authors explicitly state that they are making a contribution to the field by focusing on behavioral pathways leading to childlessness instead of contemporary correlates.
title: Pathways Into Childlessness: Evidence Of Gendered Life Course Dynamics

claim: Second, both women and men are included in the research design, which enables gendered pathways into childlessness to be examined.
explanation: The authors explicitly state that they include both women and men in their study to examine gendered pathways into childlessness.
title: Pathways Into Childlessness: Evidence Of Gendered Life Course Dynamics

claim: Women with higher levels of educational attainment are more likely to remain childless, whereas men's educational attainment does not shape their likelihood of remaining childless.
explanation: The authors present an original finding that women with higher levels of education are more likely to remain childless than men.
title: Pathways Into Childlessness: Evidence Of Gendered Life Course Dynamics

claim: Women who have no breaks over the course of their employment career are less likely, whereas their male counterparts are more likely to enter parenthood.
explanation: The authors present an original finding that women with continuous employment careers are less likely to remain childless than men.
title: Pathways Into Childlessness: Evidence Of Gendered Life Course Dynamics

claim: Remaining without a partner during the fertile years is a major restriction for having children for women. Noteworthy, it appears to be an even larger restriction for men.
explanation: The authors present an original finding that remaining without a partner during the fertile years is a significant barrier to childbearing for both women and men, but more so for men.
title: Pathways Into Childlessness: Evidence Of Gendered Life Course Dynamics

claim: Men's childlessness seems to be shaped primarily by the circumstances of their marital career, as De Meester *et al*. (2005) also stated.
explanation: The authors cite previous research and present an original finding that men's childlessness is influenced by their marital history.
title: Pathways Into Childlessness: Evidence Of Gendered Life Course Dynamics

claim: Childlessness debates require a shift in focus. Concerns about the incompatibility of work with caring tasks need to be supplemented with concerns about entering and remaining in partnerships.
explanation: The authors present an original finding that addressing childlessness requires considering both work and partnership issues.
title: Pathways Into Childlessness: Evidence Of Gendered Life Course Dynamics

claim: The analysis confirms that female education is the dominant socioeconomic driver of fertility transitions in the developing world.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating the importance of female education in driving fertility transitions.
title: Race And Childlessness In America, 1988 - 2002

claim: The authors hypothesize that marriage, age at marriage, and divorce may be less important in influencing Black women's childlessness than White women's childlessness.
explanation: This claim is an original hypothesis presented by the authors based on their analysis of racial differences in factors related to childlessness.
title: Race And Childlessness In America, 1988 - 2002

claim: The authors hypothesize that high socioeconomic status should be a strong predictor of childlessness for both groups of women, but more strongly so for Blacks than for Whites.
explanation: This claim is an original hypothesis presented by the authors based on their analysis of racial differences in factors related to childlessness.
title: Race And Childlessness In America, 1988 - 2002

claim: The authors argue that upwardly mobile Blacks constrict their fertility in an effort to assimilate into mainstream upper-middle-class culture.
explanation: This claim is a theoretical argument presented by the authors based on previous studies and analysis of racial differences in childlessness.
title: Race And Childlessness In America, 1988 - 2002

claim: The authors argue that college-educated Black women have difficulty finding marital partners, yet consciously forgo nonmarital childbearing because of racial stigmas associated with single parenting.
explanation: This claim is a theoretical argument presented by the authors based on previous studies and analysis of racial differences in childlessness.
title: Race And Childlessness In America, 1988 - 2002

claim: The analysis confirms that female education is the dominant socioeconomic driver of fertility transitions in the developing world.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating the importance of female education in driving fertility transitions.
title: 8 **Are Rural Young People Stuck** In Waithood?

claim: The concept of waithood implies 'waiting' in the sense of inactivity. This is contradicted by numerous studies that show young people engaging in multiple economic activities, often simultaneously.
explanation: This claim challenges the popular discourse of 'youth in waiting', suggesting that youth are actively engaged in various economic activities.
title: 8 **Are Rural Young People Stuck** In Waithood?

claim: A narrow conceptualization of waithood as 'youth in waiting' perpetuates the idea that interventions need to keep youth occupied, without altering the adverse structural conditions in which the chances of finding meaningful employment are very low, especially in rural areas.
explanation: This claim presents a critique of the popular conceptualization of waithood and suggests that it does not address the root causes of youth unemployment.
title: 8 **Are Rural Young People Stuck** In Waithood?

claim: Africa's rural population is expanding despite ongoing urbanization, and so is the rural workforce. Agriculture, and particularly small-scale farming, is and will remain the most important source of adult and youth employment in Africa.
explanation: This claim presents a finding based on empirical data about the state of agriculture and employment in rural Africa.
title: 8 **Are Rural Young People Stuck** In Waithood?

claim: The authors use data from two sources (Stato Civile registers and Anagrafe registers) to study changes in Italian fertility over the last ten years (1995-2004).
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's use of data from two sources to study changes in Italian fertility.
title: Marcantonio Caltabiano * Has The Fertility Decline Come To An End In The Different Regions Of Italy? New Insights From A Cohort Approach

claim: The authors estimate age-specific fertility rates for the years 1997 and 1998 using a least squares procedure.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's methodology used to estimate age-specific fertility rates.
title: Marcantonio Caltabiano * Has The Fertility Decline Come To An End In The Different Regions Of Italy? New Insights From A Cohort Approach

claim: The authors use a cohort approach in order to further explore regional variation in Italian fertility.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's research methodology used to study regional variation in Italian fertility.
title: Marcantonio Caltabiano * Has The Fertility Decline Come To An End In The Different Regions Of Italy? New Insights From A Cohort Approach

claim: The authors find that for the cohorts born up until the 1960s, fertility declines and regional differences remain relevant.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis of fertility trends in Italian regions.
title: Marcantonio Caltabiano * Has The Fertility Decline Come To An End In The Different Regions Of Italy? New Insights From A Cohort Approach

claim: The authors find that for the cohorts born from the 1970s on, the speed of the fertility decline slows in the north and even comes to a halt in several regions, while continuing to drop in southern Italy.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis of fertility trends in Italian regions.
title: Marcantonio Caltabiano * Has The Fertility Decline Come To An End In The Different Regions Of Italy? New Insights From A Cohort Approach

claim: If this trend remains constant over time, cohort fertility levels in all Italian regions may eventually converge at similar levels.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis of fertility trends in Italian regions.
title: Marcantonio Caltabiano * Has The Fertility Decline Come To An End In The Different Regions Of Italy? New Insights From A Cohort Approach

claim: Birth hazards increase as her relative education increases, and may be elevated specifically among homogamous couples with high educational attainment.
explanation: This finding is particularly interesting in the German context, since childlessness in West Germany is high in general and even more elevated among highly educated women (Kreyenfeld and Konietzka 2007).
title: Fertility, Education, And Couple Dynamics: Three Essays On Childbearing Behavior In The United States And Germany

claim: Relative income and gendered work arrangements appear to play less of a role for the time to first birth transitions.
explanation: This finding is in line with expectations derived from McDonald's argument; couples who adhere to the male breadwinner model (hence a woman with little or no income and a male breadwinner) are more likely to have a strong family orientation as was already shown, albeit for the case of Germany, by Cook (2004) and Henz (2008).
title: Fertility, Education, And Couple Dynamics: Three Essays On Childbearing Behavior In The United States And Germany

claim: Highly educated homogamous couples had shorter durations to second births than homogamous couples with less education, and also in comparison to couples with a highly educated wife (partner) and a male husband (partner) with lower education.
explanation: Hence, how her education relates to the timing of a second birth within unions appears to depend upon or interact with his educational attainment, particularly among highly educated individuals.
title: Fertility, Education, And Couple Dynamics: Three Essays On Childbearing Behavior In The United States And Germany

claim: Increases in his contribution to domestic work or childcare were not significantly related to birth hazards (only in the East German subsample was an increase in his contribution to housework associated with an increase in the second birth hazards in the 1966-75 cohort).
explanation: These findings support one of the hypotheses that were developed in the prospectus for this dissertation, namely that the distribution of domestic work among the partners may not be linked significantly to birth hazards once relative socio-economic resources are controlled for in the same model.
title: Fertility, Education, And Couple Dynamics: Three Essays On Childbearing Behavior In The United States And Germany

claim: Among couples of the youngest German birth cohort (1976-85), an increase in his contribution to domestic work was significantly related to a shorter duration to the transition to parenthood.
explanation: This finding is unprecedented in the literature and may be interpreted as indicating social change in today's Germany, towards an increasing importance of more symmetrical housework arrangements for young women's considerations of having a first child in their current union (marriage or cohabitation) sooner rather than postponing the first birth.
title: Fertility, Education, And Couple Dynamics: Three Essays On Childbearing Behavior In The United States And Germany

claim: The analysis confirms that female education is the dominant socioeconomic driver of fertility transitions in the developing world.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating the importance of female education in driving fertility transitions.
title: Researchers, Religion And Childlessness

claim: Religion has a stronger influence than education in terms of intended childlessness.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating that religion may have a greater impact on fertility intentions compared to education.
title: Researchers, Religion And Childlessness

claim: Religion can be an important driver of human behaviour, in particular with respect to family decisions.
explanation: This claim is an original interpretation based on the author's analysis and research, suggesting that religion may play a significant role in influencing family-related choices.
title: Researchers, Religion And Childlessness

claim: Intended childlessness is therefore likely to be related to religion, and thus religion is a mediator for childlessness.
explanation: This claim is an original interpretation based on the author's analysis and research, suggesting that religion may act as a factor influencing intended childlessness.
title: Researchers, Religion And Childlessness

claim: Being childless towards the end of the reproductive period could imply that a woman who previously wanted to have her own children alters her fertility preferences to accommodate the fact that she is approaching the biological maximum age for childbearing and may be less able to become a mother.
explanation: This claim is an original interpretation based on the author's analysis, suggesting that women who are approaching the end of their reproductive years may change their fertility preferences due to their decreasing ability to have children.
title: Researchers, Religion And Childlessness

claim: For non-religious or less religious women this sort of coping strategy might be psychologically easier and therefore more frequent than for religious women.
explanation: This claim is an original interpretation based on the author's analysis, suggesting that non-religious or less religious women may find it easier to cope with being childless compared to religious women.
title: Researchers, Religion And Childlessness

claim: Religious female scientists may want to potentially 'give up more' in terms of career, independence and scientific recognition, in order to establish a family.
explanation: This claim is an original interpretation based on the author's analysis, suggesting that religious female researchers may prioritize family formation over career advancement.
title: Researchers, Religion And Childlessness

claim: The male fertility level is declining, the fertility pattern is moving into higher ages, and the reproduction period for men is getting shorter.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis of male fertility trends in Greece over the period 1992–2011.
title: Male Fertility In Greece: Trends And Differentials By Education Level And Employment Status

claim: The study suggests that male fertility merits further exploration.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating the importance of men's involvement in fertility research.
title: Male Fertility In Greece: Trends And Differentials By Education Level And Employment Status

claim: The analysis covers a twenty-year period, going from 1992 to 2011; within this time period notable fertility variations occurred against a rapidly changing social and economic environment.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents the scope of the study in terms of time period and context.
title: Male Fertility In Greece: Trends And Differentials By Education Level And Employment Status

claim: The Greek birth registration system provides the primary source of national data on fathers' characteristics, as it collects detailed data about both parents at the time of birth.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a unique aspect of the study's methodology.
title: Male Fertility In Greece: Trends And Differentials By Education Level And Employment Status

claim: The average male population by age, education level and employment status is deduced from two different sources: demographic statistics (Eurostat 2013a) and LFS (Eurostat 2013b; 2013c).
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a unique aspect of the study's methodology.
title: Male Fertility In Greece: Trends And Differentials By Education Level And Employment Status

claim: The study uses a decomposition method to dissociate the impact of compositional effects (education differentials and employment status variations) from behavioral effects (fluctuations in fertility) on the above-mentioned variations of TFR.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a unique analytical approach used in the study.
title: Male Fertility In Greece: Trends And Differentials By Education Level And Employment Status

claim: The analysis confirms that there is a positive relationship between couples' happiness and their likelihood of having a first child.
explanation: The authors find that happier couples are more likely to have a first child.
title: It Takes Two To Tango: Couples' Happiness And Childbearing

claim: For the transition to second child, the study finds that both low and high levels of women's happiness are associated with a lower risk of having a second child.
explanation: The authors find that women who experience a low level of happiness might not be willing to have an additional child because they are already struggling with one child or they are having a not so positive experience with the first child. Women who are very happy may instead not want to have another child not to change the positive status quo in which they live.
title: It Takes Two To Tango: Couples' Happiness And Childbearing

claim: The study finds a multiplicative effect of the SWB of both partners on the decision to have a child.
explanation: The authors find that when both the woman and the man report a particularly high level of happiness, the probability of becoming parents for the first time increases more than when only one of the two partners is happier than usual.

claim: The study finds gender asymmetry in the sense that the female partner's SWB tends to weigh more heavily than that of the male partner.

claim: The findings not only reveal the ideological foundations of adoption and medicine, but also the power of such foundations. Individuals draw on notions of biological privilege and pronatalism to inform their understandings of adoption and medicalized infertility—adoption remains a stigmatized process for failing to adhere to such prescriptions, yet medicine is revered for maintaining them.

claim: The stigma surrounding adoption can be attributed to the primacy of genetic ties, or biological privilege, present in American society.

claim: The findings ultimately demonstrate the falsehood of those images.

claim: The study that we report here is the product of several years of ethnographic, focus group, survey design, and pilot study research to devise a general population measure of the emotional bond between husbands and wives for a specific South Asian setting: Nepal.

explanation: The authors find that educational prestige is not positively associated with fatherhood, but they observe a positive association between 2-year degrees and fatherhood.

claim: The decision-making process preceding both early and postponed first childbirth is often implicit.
explanation: The authors state that the decision to have a first child, among couples in their study, was generally quite implicit.
title: Couples' Decisions To Have A First Child: Comparing Pathways To Early And Late Parenthood

claim: Older parents more often explicitly assured themselves of their partner's wish for a child early in the relationship than young parents.
explanation: The authors state that older parents more often explicitly discussed having children with their partners early in the relationship, while young couples agreed implicitly more often on having children.
title: Couples' Decisions To Have A First Child: Comparing Pathways To Early And Late Parenthood

claim: Veto power can cause postponement of having children or even union dissolution.
explanation: The authors discuss how veto power, i.e., both partners having the right to consent before trying to have a child, can lead to separation if the disagreement about having children seems irreconcilable.
title: Couples' Decisions To Have A First Child: Comparing Pathways To Early And Late Parenthood

claim: Some men and women are quite indifferent towards having children and are easily convinced if their partner wants to have children.
explanation: The authors state that some men and women do not care much about having children and are easily convinced by their partner's wish for children.
title: Couples' Decisions To Have A First Child: Comparing Pathways To Early And Late Parenthood

claim: Anticipated loss of freedom, adjustment of lifestyle, and responsibilities were more common among older parents.
explanation: The authors state that some older parents had doubts about having children either when they were still single or after meeting their partner, and these doubts were related to the anticipated limitations in their freedom, lifestyle, and responsibilities.
title: Couples' Decisions To Have A First Child: Comparing Pathways To Early And Late Parenthood

claim: Highly educated parents did not consciously plan the birth of their child in relation to their career.
explanation: The authors state that some highly educated parents did not start thinking seriously about having children until they had finished their studies and worked at least for a few years, which implies that they did not deliberately plan the first child in relation to their career.
title: Couples' Decisions To Have A First Child: Comparing Pathways To Early And Late Parenthood

claim: Young parents often do not bother about the potential limitation to one's freedom due to childbirth.
explanation: The authors state that young parents often do not worry about practical arrangements, like finances or work and care logistics, when deciding to have a child.
title: Couples' Decisions To Have A First Child: Comparing Pathways To Early And Late Parenthood

claim: The study provides for the first time for a large number of European countries a comprehensive account of educational differences in the cohort fertility rate (CFR) at the sub-national regional level.
explanation: The authors explicitly state that they are providing a comprehensive account of educational differences in CFRs at the sub-national regional level for a large number of European countries.

claim: The study documents an overall negative gradient between the CFR and level of education, and notable variation in the gradient across sub-national regions.
explanation: The authors document that there is a negative relationship between educational attainment and CFRs, and that this relationship varies across sub-national regions.
title: Educational Diferences In Cohort Fertility Across Sub‑National Regions In Europe

claim: The steepness of the gradient is inversely related to the economic development level.
explanation: The authors find that the slope of the relationship between educational attainment and CFRs decreases as the level of economic development increases.
title: Educational Diferences In Cohort Fertility Across Sub‑National Regions In Europe

claim: Within countries, educational differences in fertility also tend to be smaller as the level of economic development of a region increases.
explanation: The authors find that within countries, there is a tendency for educational differences in fertility to decrease as the level of economic development of a region increases.
title: Educational Diferences In Cohort Fertility Across Sub‑National Regions In Europe

claim: In some countries, the educational gradient is not associated or positively associated with the level of GDP of a region.
explanation: The authors find that in some countries, there is no relationship or a positive relationship between educational attainment and CFRs and the level of economic development of a region.
title: Educational Diferences In Cohort Fertility Across Sub‑National Regions In Europe

claim: The study examines how individuals perceive children, focusing on two dimensions—the positive aspects of having children and the perception of children as a burden—and taking into account relations with both individual- and macro-level characteristics.

claim: The authors find that women who consistently recall having had limited or very limited leisure time in the first period of their union seem more likely to forego motherhood.

claim: Individuals who attend services on a regular basis (at least once a month) will have larger family size compared with those who attend services less often or not at all.

claim: Nominally affiliated individuals (those identifying with a particular religion but do not attend services on a regular basis) would have smaller family size compared with religiously active individuals, though larger than those who stated having no religious affiliation.

claim: Fertility differences between regular and non-regular service attendants will increase among younger birth cohorts.

claim: More religious women, in terms of affiliation and practice, would be more likely to experience the transition to first birth and that this gap will increase among the younger birth cohorts.

claim: Geographic accessibility to assisted reproduction is significantly higher in the most advantaged local authorities in terms of average household income and level of deprivation.

claim: Self-employment is associated with larger declines in expected fertility, but this relationship washes out at higher parity levels.

claim: 'The overall relationship between home based work (HBW) and fertility intentions among Polish parents during the Covid-19 pandemic was negative (H1a), at least among mothers (H1b). In other words, we expect that fertility intentions of parents (mothers in particular) who worked from home declined more strongly or increased less strongly than fertility intentions of their ofce-based counterparts.'
explanation: 'The authors explicitly state that they expect to find a negative relationship between HBW and fertility intentions among mothers, as they were the ones to bear the most of the additional unpaid work during the pandemic (e.g., Sevilla & Smith, 2020).'

title: Working From Home During Covid‑19 Pandemic And Changes To Fertility Intentions Among Parents

claim: 'For mothers holding jobs characterized by low autonomy, which are not suited to be executed from home, working from home while at the same time taking care of a child/children might have resulted in signifcant drop in their work satisfaction and as a consequence—led to increased fertility intentions.'

claim: The analysis of adolescent contexts on adulthood childbearing rates makes five contributions to immigrant fertility research.
explanation: First, the early-life childbearing attitudes association to later fertility may be extended to near completed fertility, not just first births as found in the research of Guzzo et al. (2019) and in Chapter 1. Second, racial/ethnic and nativity variation in childbearing rates are only significant among those with lenient early childbearing attitudes. This second point lends support to immigrant fertility subculture theories, because, as shown in Chapter 2, foreign-born groups are more inclined to have lenient or neutral early childbearing attitudes. In the present chapter this proclivity among foreign-born groups is linked to higher childbearing rates and predicted births. Third, the proportion foreign-born in neighborhoods substantially increases childbearing rates for all ethnoracial nativity subgroups, except among US-born Black women. Yet the influence of the proportion foreign-born in neighborhoods is only significant among foreign-born groups. Fourth, the proportion foreign-born in schools affects childbearing rates in opposite directions among US- and foreign-born groups, though results are only significant among US-born Black women. The different effects at the school and tract-level of aggregation for immigrant concentration point to different socialization experiences in adolescence. Notably, the fertility increasing effect of neighborhood immigrant composition across most ethnoracial nativity subgroups likely points to broader structural factors of residential segregation, as has been found in European contexts (Wilson and Kuha 2017). In the US, research finds that adolescent exposure to neighborhood poverty increases the risk of teenage childbearing (Wodtke 2013), but it is unclear how this applied to immigrant subgroups. Lastly, predicted births at the intersection of ethnoracial nativity subgroup's early childbearing attitudes across immigrant contexts reflect the general fertility-increasing effects of lenient early childbearing attitudes.

claim: Discriminatory treatment in reproductive healthcare settings can impede access to important medical care, such as cervical cancer screening (Agénor et al., 2015; Curmi et al., 2016; Johnson, Mueller, Eliason, Stuart, & Nemeth, 2016) and prenatal care (Light et al., 2014).

claim: Pregnant sexual minority women were more likely to have unmet medical care needs owing to cost compared with pregnant heterosexual women.

claim: Pregnant sexual minority women were more likely to smoke cigarettes every day compared with other women.

title: Health And Access To Care Among Reproductive-Age Women By Sexual Orientation And Pregnancy Status

claim: Pregnant sexual minority women were more likely to report frequent mental distress, depression, poor/fair health, activity limitations, chronic conditions, and risky health behaviors compared with pregnant heterosexual women.

title: Health And Access To Care Among Reproductive-Age Women By Sexual Orientation And Pregnancy Status

claim: Nonpregnant sexual minority women were more likely to report barriers to care, activity limitations, chronic conditions, smoking, and binge drinking compared with nonpregnant heterosexual women.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating that nonpregnant sexual minority women have worse health outcomes compared to nonpregnant heterosexual women.

claim: It is recommended to discuss these options at time of planning for gender-affirming hormonal therapy (GAHT) or engaging with other gender-affirming procedures that can limit future fertility.

explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a summary of the main themes that emerged from the analysis of the interviews conducted with women in same-sex relationships.

claim: The analysis confirms that there are no statistically significant differences between the TTC and PP groups in mean EPDS scores.
